Similar topologies of individual‐based plant‐herbivorous networks in forest interior and anthropogenic edges

Raquel L Carvalho
Diego V Anjos
Roberth Fagundes
Pedro Luna
Sérvio Pontes Ribeiro
First published: 28 January 2021
https://doi.org/10.1111/aec.13001
Sections
PDF
Tools
Share

Abstract

Understanding the impacts of edge effects on ecological interactions plays an integral role in planning ecosystem recovery from human perturbations, as well as conservation of habitats. Edge effects related to forest fragmentation cause changes in species diversity that can disrupt ecological networks. Here, we evaluated how the diversity of, and interactions between, herbivorous insects associated with individuals of a pioneer plant species, Mabea fistulifera (Euphorbiaceae) are affected by the disturbances related to edge effects. We addressed two specific questions: (i) How do the forest edges affect species richness, abundance and composition of herbivorous interacting with M. fistulifera? (ii) Do different disturbances related to edge effects affect the topology of individual‐based plant‐herbivorous networks? Herbivorous insects were sampled from three population patches of M. fistulifera in Brazilian Atlantic forest areas: two areas were subjected to distinct intensities of anthropogenic disturbances (firebreak and park access road, considered edges of low‐ and high‐impact, respectively), and one in the forest interior (control). We expected a lower species richness and abundance of herbivorous interacting with plants in forest edges than in the forest interior apart from to differences in the species composition. Therefore, based on these predictions, we expected that the various disturbances related to edge effects may change the topology of individual‐based plant‐herbivorous networks. We observed that species richness and abundance of herbivorous in high‐impact environments decreased in relation to forest interior, as well the species composition differed between these areas. Disturbance jeopardised network specialisation but did not change the topology of individual‐based networks, which presented a modular pattern. Edges affected herbivorous diversity and decreased the interaction overlap as individual‐based networks became highly specialised with increasing disturbance. These results enhance the understanding of edge effects and resilience of plant‐herbivorous interactions in regularly disturbed tropical environments.

Introduction

Anthropogenic disturbances caused by fragmentation of natural ecosystems are important drivers of habitat modification in the remaining natural ecological communities (Murcia 1995). Species diversity decline and loss of ecosystem functions are among the most important changes (Fahrig 2003; Lourenço et al. 2019). For instance, anthropogenic borders of a fragmented forest are subject to the edge effect, which is characterised by presenting different biotic (e.g. species diversity) and mainly abiotic conditions (e.g. temperature, luminosity, wind speed and air humidity) compared to forest interior (Williams‐Linera 1990; Magnago et al. 2015). Such modified environmental conditions in forest edges tend to affect species diversity and ecological interactions (De Carvalho et al. 2014, Pinho et al. 2017) through differential land use (De Araújo et al. 2015; Benítez‐Malvido et al. 2016; Alves‐Silva et al. 2020) and shifting environmental stressors (López‐Carretero et al. 2014). As such, edges favour mostly generalist species such as pioneers and exotics (Harper et al. 2005).

In general, plant species adjust their growth form (Yamada et al., 2000), chemical defences (Yamawo et al. 2014), nutrient absorption (Chapin, 1983) and other traits under different abiotic conditions such as forest edges. As conditions change from forest to open vegetation, pioneer plant species are favoured mainly due to increased temperature and light availability (Laurance et al. 2006; Santos et al. 2010). These pioneer plants create a dynamic and quickly variable habitat for arthropod fauna, favouring generalist herbivorous insects, for instance (Valladares et al. 2006; Rossetti et al. 2017). Herbivorous insects take advantage of the greater tissue nutrient concentration, better palatability of these tissues and the low investment of these plants in defences against herbivory (Coley et al., 1985; Fortin & Mauffette 2001; Ribeiro et al. 2008). In addition, these insects have greater oviposition rates in sun‐light leaves (Moore et al. 1988). Herbivorous can drive plant diversity in the tropics, affecting the distribution of species through predation and parasitism of seeds and seedlings (Janzen 1970; Bagchi et al. 2014). Herbivorous also limit the growth rates of populations, influencing habitat colonisation and even speciation (Fine et al. 2004; Ribeiro & Brown 2006). Therefore, herbivory along with pollination, are remarkable plant–animal interactions (Crawley 1983). For conservation, it is crucial to understand how edge disturbances change the properties of interaction networks and how these properties vary over space and time (Valladares et al. 2006; Pinho et al. 2017).

In the Atlantic forest, the pioneer plant species Mabea fistulifera Mart. (Euphorbiaceae) can be found in both the edge and the interior of forest fragments (Campos et al. 2006; Ribeiro et al. 2008). Mabea fistulifera has the capacity to live in open environments and to overcome shade in the forest interior by adjusting its crown architecture to small canopy spaces (Carvalho & Ribeiro 2018). Just as environmental conditions, the presence of latex in M. fistulifera may function as a filter for generalist insects, which are unable to deal with large amounts of latex (Dussourd & Eisner 1987; Farrell et al. 1991). Our group's previous studies on M. fistulifera have recorded few species and low abundance of herbivorous insects per tree, with Curculionidae, Chrysomelidae and Anobiidae being the most dominant herbivorous families (Ribeiro et al. 2008). The beetle Syphraea spp. (Coleoptera: Chrysomelidae) is a restricted specialist herbivorous of M. fistulifera because it can deactivate latex channels by cutting veins (Becerra 1994, Williams, 1991). Therefore, M. fistulifera trees in the forest interior are attacked by this restricted fauna of specialist herbivorous that can break its defences and therefore build stable herbivory interactions. However, M. fistulifera in the forest edges, besides to exhibiting less structural complexity (e.g. lower height and fewer twigs, leaves and branches) (Carvalho & Ribeiro 2018), may not have the same line of defences as forest interior trees and could be attacked by several different opportunist herbivorous (Wirth et al. 2008). This can impact in the plant's fitness and then in forest recovery.

The Complex Networks Theory has been an important tool for understanding how anthropogenic disturbances affect not only species diversity but also their trophic interactions (López‐Carretero et al. 2014; Falcão et al. 2015; Fagundes et al. 2018; Alves‐Silva et al. 2020). However, this approach has focused mainly on community‐level interactions (i.e. interspecific interactions) (but see Benítez‐Malvido et al. 2014, 2016). For instance, in a global review considering community‐based plant‐herbivorous networks, the land use intensity and network specialisation (the level at which species interact with more species) presented a positive relationship due to the reduction of host plants of herbivorous guilds with highly specialised feeding habits (De Araújo et al. 2015). Pinho et al. (2017) showed that the edge effect affects negatively the structure and stability of plant‐herbivorous networks. This classic interspecific approach has been used to understand many aspects of community dynamics, ignoring that the individuals of a population can interact with others species in different ways, which influences the structure of their interactions under a network approach (Pires et al. 2011; Benítez‐Malvido et al. 2014, 2016). In bipartite individual‐based networks, nodes of one trophic level are represented by different individuals of the same population and the other trophic level is represented by the species with which the individuals interact (Pires et al. 2011). This approach also can be an important tool in conservation studies, for instance, showing the importance of how a single plant species may offer food and habitat for associated fauna in human‐impacted landscapes (Benítez‐Malvido et al. 2014, 2016). As M. fistulifera is often used in forest recovery plans, their ecological interactions with herbivorous (e.g. individual‐based networks) under different disturbances related to edge effects can tell us about their true role in forest recovery and in habitat conservation. For instance, individual‐based plant‐herbivorous networks which exhibit a nested pattern of interactions, due to specialist species (e.g. Syphraea spp.) that tend to interact with a core subset of M. fistulifera individuals which presents specific interactions with other herbivorous, can increase the plant growth and/or their fitness in disturbed environments where these specialist species are absent or less abundant (Wimp et al. 2011; Rossetti et al. 2017).

Our study aimed to assess whether different disturbances related to edge effects (firebreak and park access road, considered low‐ and high‐impact, respectively) affect the diversity of herbivorous insects associated with individuals of a dominant plant species and the consequences of possible changes in diversity in individual‐based plant‐herbivorous networks. Our study addresses two specific questions: (i) How do the forest edges affect species richness, abundance and composition of herbivorous interacting with M. fistulifera? (ii) Do different disturbances related to edge effects change the topology of individual plant‐herbivorous networks? We expected a lower species richness and abundance of herbivorous interacting with plants in forest edges than in the forest interior (Rossetti et al. 2017), reducing frequency of interactions in forest edges. We also predicted differences in the species composition, with trees in the edges presenting a subset of the herbivorous species associated with trees in the forest interior (Benítez‐Malvido et al. 2014, 2016), and a lack of specialist herbivorous in favour of generalist herbivorous (Tscharntke et al. 2002; Wirth et al. 2008; Rossetti et al. 2017). Finally, based on these predictions, we expected that the various disturbances related to edge effects may change the topology of individual‐based plant‐herbivorous networks. Moreover, if diversity of specialist herbivorous is lower with increasing disturbances, the interactions might display lower niche breadth and overlap (i.e. lower nestedness, higher specialisation and higher modularity).

Materials and Methods

Study area

We worked in the Atlantic forest of south‐eastern Brazil, one of the most fragmented and disturbed ecosystems in the world (Ribeiro et al. 2009). The study site is located in Parque Estadual do Rio Doce (hereafter, PERD; 19º30' ‐ 19º48'S, 42º30 ‐ 42º36'W), in the state of Minas Gerais. The park covers 35 973 ha and is the last large remnant of Atlantic forest in Minas Gerais. The elevation ranges in from 200 m to 500 m a. s. l. Most of the vegetation at PERD consists of the domain of the Atlantic semideciduous forest (Lourenço et al. 2019). The regional climate is warm and humid, with temperatures fluctuating between 28ºC and 39ºC in the wet season, and between 7ºC and 20ºC in the dry season. Annual precipitation varies between 1350 mm and 1900 mm (De Paula et al. 2002).

Plant species

We studied Mabea fistulifera Mart. (Euphorbiaceae), a dominant pioneer species in the region and an essential species in natural succession. Mabea fistulifera is classified as medium‐sized, semideciduous, heliophytic and arboreal. It is found in low open forest and disturbed forests (Carvalho & Ribeiro 2018) and is an essential component of the park's low and open forest canopies. This species has bat pollination syndrome, thus large pollen dispersion, capable of connecting patches, typically found in disturbed spots or forest edges in a forest ecosystem (Goulart et al. 2005). As a consequence, there is substantial genetic variability inside population patches, but little variability between‐population patches inside a forest (Goulart et al. 2005). Flowering occurs from January to May with peak flowering occurring at the beginning of the dry season in April and May. Extrafloral nectaries and domatia are absent in M. fistulifera; its trunk, branches and leaves accumulate a large amount of latex (Lorenzi 1992). When occurring in edges of forest fragments, this species tends to predominate in the tree line, on the actual edge between the forest and the disturbed/modified landscape. This study system is part of the Rio Doce Long‐term ecological research, and the M. fistulifera populations have been under investigation since 1999 (Goulart et al. 2005; Campos et al. 2006; Ribeiro et al. 2008).

Sample design

We focused on low forest habitat (10–20 m tree height) in the southern part of the PERD. This focus on a single forest type eliminated the effect of additional habitats, such as those created by the presence of emergent trees. We sampled the insect herbivorous fauna on individuals of three M. fistulifera populations patches in environments with different disturbance levels. As ecological control (i.e. a population subject only to sporadic natural disturbances), we took samples from one M. fistulifera population in a forest interior area (hereafter 'forest interior') at least 350 metres from the natural edge, in which there are no recorded M. fistulifera individuals. Forest interior can be referred to as late secondary forest and is composed of a mix of persistent and pioneer tree species (mainly M. fistulifera) with a preserved and well‐developed canopy. Mabea fistulifera in the forest interior has an upper canopy about 15 m, on average.

We studied two anthropogenic edges adjacent to forest environments: i) forest edge adjacent to a firebreak line (hereafter 'low‐impact edge') and ii) forest edge adjacent to a park access road (hereafter 'high‐impact edge') (Fig. 1). The low‐impact edge is between secondary fire‐disturbed forest and a farm dominated by abandoned pastures on floodable soil, in an area continuous to the park. This edge was formed in 1944 using bulldozers; the last forest fire in the area was in 1997. The firebreak is approximately ten metres wide and is cleaned manually by humans with the pruning of some shrubs and branches every 3–4 years (at the beginning of the dry season). The firebreak is continuously monitored and maintained to suppress plant growth; however, none of our individuals were affected. The surroundings were recovering naturally by succession. The canopy is composed of trees rarely exceeding 10 m in height. This area is 13 km from the first population (forest interior). The high‐impact edge is between two secondary forest fragments and was initially disturbed by road construction in the 1940s. Since then, this environment has been disturbed daily by human activities, mainly through road management and vehicles. The road edge has more disturbance as the vegetation of the edge and surroundings are continually suppressed to prevent road blockage. The high‐impact edge is also polluted by car traffic in the road. In the high‐impact edge, M. fistulifera individuals are young (rarely reaching 5 m in height) compared to the populations of the other environments; they were planted in 1994 to restore a disturbed forest remnant close to a park road. This area is located 6 km from the forest interior and 15 km from the low‐impact edge.

The forest edges we investigated are dominated by M. fistulifera. We sampled the trees in the forest edges up to five metres away from the edge (Fontoura et al. 2006). Given that M. fistulifera presents greater within‐population genetic variability than between‐population variability (Goulart et al. 2005), we concentrated our sampling effort on the number of individuals within each population/environment. Despite the individual's height shows considerable variation among environments ‐ within each environment, we sampled 15 trees of similar height and at least 20 m apart (N = 45 individuals of M. fistulifera). We choose adult plants because the leaves of adults accumulate large amounts of latex and the herbivorous fauna at this stage is similar and persistent for long periods (SP Ribeiro personal observation).

Herbivorous insect sampling

We sampled nine trees (three in each environment) per day. Each day, new trees were sampled, totalising five consecutive days (total of 5 days × 9 trees per day per environment = 45 independent trees), per sampling event. We used a standardised sampling order of the trees and sites. These individuals were tagged and sampled during the study period. This same sampling effort was made in the wet and dry seasons for two consecutive years, totalising four sampling events. Specifically, we sampled all individuals on sunny days in February (wet season) and July (dry season) of 2011 and 2012. We sampled insects, between 9:00 am and 3:30 pm each day; this corresponded with the period of greatest insect activity (Neves et al. 2013). Despite sampling at different stations, individuals had similar phenological conditions during sampling events (Goulart et al. 2005). Insects in the crowns of M. fistulifera were sampled by beating (Ribeiro et al. 2005). An adapted entomological umbrella was put under three branches of each randomly chosen tree, and each branch was hit ten times to remove the fauna (see Ribeiro et al. 2005). To access the tree crowns in the canopy, we used single‐rope and safety‐free climbing techniques (Ribeiro & Basset 2007; Neves et al. 2013). This technique has been shown to be a good proxy to measure antagonistic interactions such as herbivory (Wardhaugh et al. 2015; Augustyn et al. 2016; Oliveira et al. 2019).

Samples were frozen and transported to the laboratory for processing, identification and enumeration. Coleoptera and Hemiptera individuals were identified to the lowest taxonomic level using keys in Borror et al. (2002), and to species level, when possible, by comparison with named species in the 'Laboratório de Ecologia Evolutiva de Insetos de Dossel e Sucessão Natural' of Federal University of Ouro Preto. Collection vouchers were also deposited at the Federal University of Ouro Preto. We only included species as herbivorous insects after checking their mouthparts and feeding habits (Borror et al. 2002). Species that could not be confidently named were assigned morphospecies number codes that apply only to this study. We choose Coleoptera and Hemiptera insects because they are the main group of chewing herbivorous and sucking herbivorous, respectively (Borror et al. 2002). In addition, the number of immature Lepidoptera was irrelevant, and the few individuals falling down in the entomologic umbrella were normally too damaged to allow identification at any sort. Furthermore, previous work from our group on insect herbivorous on this M. fistulifera population already showed little relevance of Lepidoptera group on the insect herbivorous assembly (Ribeiro et al. 2008).

Data analysis

As the data set was small in each sampling event, we decided to group them (four sampling events) and apply a more complete approach towards our goal. We considered each tree as a sample (n = 15 for each area) and measured herbivorous richness (number of species) and abundance (number of individuals) as dependent variables of each sample. As explanatory variables, we used the type of environment: forest edges (low and high‐impact edges) and forest interior (control). To evaluate differences in herbivorous richness and abundance between populations of all three environments, we used generalised linear models (GLMs) with quasi‐Poison error distribution. When models indicated differences in explanatory variables, we made post hoc comparisons with the multcomp package (Bretz et al. 2010). We checked the adequacy of each model by examining the distribution of residuals (Crawley 2012). We used the relative abundance of herbivorous species per tree to calculate the similarity between the trees of all three environments (Bray–Curtis Index). We used ANOSIM models followed by a Bonferroni paired test to evaluate differences in composition of herbivorous species interacting with M. fistulifera individuals of all three environments. Based on the same similarity matrix, we built an ordering graph using the NMDS model to represent the difference between trees of all three environments. We conducted GLMs and post hoc analysis in R 3.5.3 platform (R Core Team 2019) using the interface Action 3.2 (Statcamp), and ANOSIM and NMDS in the software PAST 3.16 (Hammer et al. 2001).

To evaluate the edge effects on the interactions among individual plants and their herbivorous insects, we used a network analysis using tools derived from the Complex Networks Theory (Jordano et al. 2003; Blüthgen et al. 2006; Almeida‐Neto et al. 2008). To search for differences in plant‐herbivorous network topology, we constructed incidence matrices, where aij = number of interactions an individual tree i with herbivorous insect j, and 0 where there are none. We considered the number of interactions as abundance of herbivorous insects (number of individuals) in each sampling event accumulated over time. We constructed three matrices: i) the interactions in the forest interior, ii) the interactions in the low‐impact edge and iii) the interactions in the high‐impact edge. Each matrix represents the interaction of 15 trees with their herbivorous, enabling analysis of the variation of interactions among a subset of the individuals of a certain population. From these matrices, we calculated network size by multiplying the number of individuals by the number of herbivorous in the network, which gives us an estimate of the number of possible interactions. We also calculated the degree (number of interactions) of the networks; the number of interactions that each tree shared with herbivorous morphospecies (shared partners), as a measure of herbivorous' interaction niche width (Jordano et al. 2003). To measure the overlap and niche breath at a network level, we used the complementary specialisation of the interactions ( Index) (Blüthgen et al. 2006). This index measures the specialisation of a network assuming that rare interactions do not reflect real specialisation, and it ranges from 0 (completely generalist network, complete overlap of interactions) to 1 (completely specialised network, no overlap of interactions). We evaluated the significance of the index (i.e. if the observed index value differs from a value obtained by a null model) for each of the studied sites: interior forest, low and high‐impact edge. To achieve this, we simulated 1000 null networks of each the studied sites (1000 iterations per network), using the Patefield algorithm (Patefield 1981). With the simulated null networks we estimated 1000 values, and then we compared if the observed value of differed from the ones obtained by the null model.

To further explore if there were differences between the studied networks, we tested whether the absolute difference in the observed values of was higher than would be expected in simulated networks generated by a null model using Patefield algorithm (Patefield 1981). Using this approach, we first estimated the values of two observed networks; then we estimated the difference between both values. Further, to assess if the observed differences in the values of are not a results of randomness, we simulated 1000 null networks of each of the networks to be compared (1000 iterations per network), we then estimated the index for the iterated networks and estimated its differences (by subtraction) to obtain 1000 values of the expected differences between the two focal networks. In the end we compared if the observed difference of the index differs from the differences obtained by iterating the differences with null models. We compared the observed and simulated differences in values between i) forest interior and the low‐impact edge networks, ii) forest interior and the high‐impact edge networks, and iii) low‐impact and high‐impact networks; 1000 interactions were simulated for each of the three comparisons (i, ii and iii). Furthermore, to search for non‐random patterns of interactions (i.e. topology) between a subset of herbivorous species and plant individuals, we calculated the level of nestedness (redundancy of interactions) using the WNODF‐metric method (Weighted Nestedness Metric Based on Overlap and Decreasing Fill) (Almeida‐Neto & Ulrich 2011). The nestedness values range from 0 (non‐nested) to 100 (perfectly nested). We estimated the degree of modularity (segregation of interactions) using the QuanBiMo (Q) algorithm (Dormann & Strauss 2014). This algorithm calculates the modularity for weighted networks using the Likelihood and Simulated Annealing‐Monte Carlo approach (Dormann & Strauss 2014). The modularity index (Q) ranges from 0 (no subgroups) to 1 (totally separate subgroups). Here, modules represent groups of individual plants in the populations that shared higher number of interactions of similar herbivorous species. To test whether the computed values actually reflect a non‐random structure, we applied a null model approach in which we generated 1000 random matrices, using the Patefield algorithm (Patefield 1981); we compare if the observed value differed from the ones obtained by the null model. Further, the computed values of nestedness and modularity were standardised using Z‐scores to control the differences in richness, connectance and heterogeneity among networks (e.g. network size). The Z‐transformed score is defined: Z = [x ‐ µ]/σ, where x is the observed index value, µ is the mean of the values from simulated matrices, and σ is the standard deviation of the values from simulated matrices (Almeida‐Neto et al. 2008). We estimated the significance of the network descriptors using Z‐scores (values ≥ 2) (Dormann & Strauss 2014). The value of the Z‐score shows the magnitude of the difference between the null model and the observed network descriptor, whereby a Z‐score of 7 (e.g. for modularity) means that the observed modularity is 7 standard deviations higher than would be expected from random networks. Z‐scores above 2 are considered significantly modular (2 standard deviations). Negative Z‐score values can arise if the mean of the null models is higher than the observed value, if the value is positive it indicates that the mean of the null models is lower than the observed value. Finally, to describe herbivorous species as peripheral (selective species, which have few interactions) or generalist core (‘generalist’ species, which have the most interactions) components of the networks, we used the formula proposed by Dáttilo et al. (2013): Gc = (ki − kmean)/σk, where ki = mean number of links for a given species, kmean = mean number of links for all species in the network, and σk = standard deviation of the number of links for each species. Gc > 1 are herbivorous species of the ‘generalist’ core, and Gc < 1 are peripheral herbivorous species. The index, WNODF, Q algorithms, the null models and core‐periphery formula were calculated with the ‘bipartite’ package (Dormann et al. 2017) available in R 3.5.3 platform (R Core Team 2020). We built the interaction network graphs for each environment in ‘igraph’ package (Csardi & Nepusz 2006).

Results

We found 394 herbivorous from 78 morphospecies in 45 trees of M. fistulifera (9 ± 8.68, mean ± SD of individuals per tree). This total comprised 358 coleopteran chewers from 62 morphospecies in 41 trees, and 36 hemipteran sap‐suckers from 16 morphospecies in 18 trees (Table 1). A total of 206 of these herbivorous (52%), representing 49 morphospecies, occurred in trees within the forest interior, 134 (34%) herbivorous from 32 morphospecies occurred in trees of low‐impact edge and 54 (14%) herbivorous from 28 morphospecies occurred in trees of high‐impact edge. On average, there were differences in abundance (F2,42 = 5.86, P < 0.01) and richness (F2,42 = 7.61, P < 0.01) of herbivorous insects between the three environments. The trees in forest interior only had more individuals (F2,42 = 5.7, P < 0.01) and more species of herbivorous (F2,42 = 5.3, P < 0.01) than trees in high‐impact edge (Tukey: P < 0.01, Fig. 2a, b). No difference was found between the abundance and richness of herbivorous between trees in the forest interior and low‐impact edges, neither between the anthropogenic edges (Tukey: P > 0.05).

The species composition of herbivorous populations that interacted with M. fistulifera differs depending on the environment (ANOSIM: R2 = 0.28, P < 0.01). Our results showed a similarity gradient in the herbivorous species composition, ranging from trees in the high‐impact edge to trees in both the forest interior and low‐impact edge, which form two indistinct interaction systems. Still, such differentiation happened only along axis 1 of the NMDS matrix, which explained 24% of data variation (Stress = 0.11) (Fig. 3). Trees of the high‐impact edge had 11 exclusive herbivorous morphospecies, while the trees of the low‐impact edge had 18 exclusive, and trees of the forest interior had 25 exclusive herbivorous.

The size and number of interactions of the network were higher in the forest interior (64 components, 84 interactions) when compared to the low‐impact (47, 56) and high‐impact edges (43, 37). Herbivorous morphospecies shared more plants in the forest interior (0.25 shared plants/herbivorous morphospecies) than in low‐impact (0.18) and high‐impact (0.14) edges, creating a gradient in specialisation interactions from a more generalised network in forest interior (observed  = 0.26, null‐value = 0.11 ± 0.02) to a more specialised network in low‐impact (observed  = 0.49; null‐value = 0.14 ± 0.03) and high‐impact edges (observed  = 0.60, null‐value = 0.18 ± 0.06). However, the observed differences in values did not differ between the low‐ and high‐impact networks when compared to the randomised differences of values. Whereas, the low‐ and high‐impact networks had a greater complementary specialisation when compared to the interior network (Table 2).

In the forest interior, three species, Parasyphraea spp. (CAP1) and dominant herbivorous of Syphraea spp. (CAS1 and CAS2), formed the generalist core of the network (69.4% of the total interactions measured), while 46 other species had few interactions and alternated between trees already occupied by interactive dominant morphospecies (Fig. 4a). In the low‐impact edge, the network's generalist core species were Syphraea spp. (CAS1 and CAS2) and Apion spp. (CAA1) with 64.1% of the total interactions measured; these species acted as a hub in the network, while many other trees presented interactions only with exclusive herbivorous species (Fig. 4b). In the high‐impact edge, seven herbivorous species (CAS1, CAS2, CAA1, M13, F11 and UB7) act as a generalist core with 42.5% of the total interactions (Fig. 4c).

Based on the network approach, we found weak differences in the topology of plant‐herbivorous networks in the forest interior and the forest edges. The interactions observed in the forest interior were not nested (WNODF = 10.32, Z‐score = 0.40, P = 0.30), but they presented a modular network structure (Q = 0.38, Z‐score = 7.88, P < 0.01). The plant‐herbivorous network in the low‐impact edge also resulted in a non‐nested (WNODF = 7.96, Z‐score = −3.83, P < 0.01) and modular network (Q = 0.55, Z‐score = 12.46, P < 0.01). In the high‐impact edge the network topology was similar to the previous ones: non‐nested (WNODF = 2.25, Z‐score = −2.7, p < 0.01) and modular network (Q = 0.7, Z‐score = 6.7, P < 0.01).

Discussion

In this study we showed that the species richness, abundance and composition of herbivorous in association with M. fistulifera were affected by higher intensity of edge effects caused by anthropogenic disturbances in the original forest. Our findings corroborate similar results for the tropical plant communities (De Carvalho et al. 2014). Moreover, this is the first study, to our knowledge, that uses an individual‐based plant‐herbivorous network approach to explore edge effects. We show that the specialisation of individual‐based networks is lower in forest interior than in the networks of low‐ and high‐impact edges. Such finding suggests that the intensity of anthropogenic disturbance decreases the overlap and niche breadth of individual‐based plant‐herbivorous networks, regardless of the fact that network modularity remains constant in the three environments. Due to the modular nature of the networks, we observed networks with subgroups of herbivorous that interact more with subgroups of tree individuals than with other individuals in the same network, thus the lesser diversity of herbivorous the greater likelihood of a reduction in the niche overlap of the whole assemblage (Augustyn et al. 2016). We have to mention that the specialisation index implemented by us considers the interactions of all the individuals and their herbivorous, therefore its interpretation must be made at a community level. Therefore, specialisation changes can be explained by the absence or low frequency of specialist herbivorous (e.g. Syphraea spp.: CAS1 and CAS2) in the forest edges. In general, these changes in interactions between herbivorous insects and their host plants may lead to decreased rates of herbivory, enabling the rapid growth of these individuals in forest edges (Valladares et al. 2006; Wirth et al. 2008 and therein).

We found that M. fistulifera individuals in forest interior maintain an abundant and broadly diverse herbivorous fauna, dominated mainly by the specialist herbivorous (e.g. Syphraea spp., Chrysomelidae), which can tolerate the plant's latex defence (Becerra 1994; Williams, 1991). Two factors that may contribute to the higher diversity of herbivorous interactions (mainly considering specialist herbivorous) in the forest interior are the higher stability of abiotic conditions and the greater diversity of microhabitats due to plant traits (Ries et al. 2004; Campos et al. 2006; Ribeiro et al. 2008). For instance, M. fistulifera individuals in the forest interior can offer large amounts of resources (e.g. number of leaves, twigs and branches) to herbivorous insect fauna. Forest interior M. fistulifera can provide enemy‐free spaces (e.g. ants) for breeding and feeding (Ribeiro et al. 2005; Ribeiro & Borges 2010) because individuals of M. fistulifera are in average four metres taller than those in the edges and present almost twice the amount of leaves (higher complexity) than those in the low‐impact edges (Carvalho & Ribeiro 2018). We cannot disregard that differences in the microclimate produced by the edge effect can change the nutritive and defensive characteristics of some plants. Some forest edge plants may have less direct defences such as leaf toughness, chemical defences and trichomes (Yamawo et al. 2014) and greater nutritional quality of tissues (Angold, 1997). These changes may have favoured more generalist species such as Membracidae sp. 10 (Wood 1993), which was only sampled in high‐impact edges. Implications of these possible changes (e.g. nutritional content and defence against herbivory) in the topology of individual‐based plant‐herbivorous network need to be investigated.

Although the abundance of herbivorous insects is an important factor for network structure, null models help to prevent this factor from interfering with network metrics. In addition, changes in the abundance of herbivorous insects are also a natural consequence of anthropogenic disturbances (Valladares et al. 2006; De Carvalho et al. 2014). We found that the plant‐herbivorous networks in low‐ and high‐impact edges were smaller (network size), interaction frequency was lower, specialisation was higher, and the network topology was modular.

Although the trend is that small networks exhibit a nonmodular pattern (Olesen et al. 2007), modularity is expected to increase with interactions specificity, such as plant‐herbivorous networks (Prado and Lewinsohn, 2004; Cagnolo et al. 2011; Robinson & Strauss 2020). Here, we have shown that the modular pattern also appears in individual‐based networks. This modular pattern may show that the loss of some herbivorous (e.g. through anthropogenic disturbance) can favour their respective host individuals without causing any major consequences for the network as a whole. Our findings contradict those for community‐level plant‐herbivorous networks (i.e. based on plant species instead of individuals), whose specialisation (at species level) and modularity are lower in high‐stress conditions (e.g. anthropogenic edges) than in forest interior (Pinho et al. 2017). However, Robinson and Strauss (2020) used plant‐herbivorous networks under stressful conditions to show that the modular pattern of the network is maintained. Regarding individual‐based networks that do not consider only herbivorous (Heliconia‐invertebrates network), the network metrics also are maintained in anthropogenic habitats independent of location and plant species (Benítez‐Malvido et al. 2014). The similarity in the structure of the networks also indicates that, despite the disturbances, the network structure remains similar, reflecting resilience to extinctions or perturbations (Olesen et al. 2007). Moreover, the maintenance of the pattern found suggests that even in impacted environments, which presents lose some herbivorous species, the most part of herbivory is maintained due to the modular structure, for instance. However, if this herbivorous loss increases and persists over time, the decrease in herbivory pressure can lead to higher growth rates and plant persistence, delaying the natural succession.

Importantly, the variation in traits between individuals is subtler than the variation between species (Tur et al. 2014). Edge effects lead to impressive changes in the development and architecture of Heliconia individuals in Mexican tropical forest (Benítez‐Malvido et al. 2014, 2016) as well as in M. fistulifera individuals (e.g. more vertical growth, shorter stems without branches) (Carvalho & Ribeiro 2018). These broad individual variations probably generate specific interactions between individuals and their herbivorous insects. Some herbivorous become more selective or limited to specific groups of individuals, probably those with better resources and lower foraging cost (Boaventura et al. 2018; Carvalho & Ribeiro 2018). For instance, Syphraea spp. (e.g. CAS2) in forest interior were present in 14 of the 15 trees sampled, but they occupied only three out of 15 trees in the high‐impact edge. Therefore, the greater specialisation in low‐ and high‐impact edges may reflect: (1) individual trait variability (e.g. plant height, number of branches, crown architecture, host individual genotype) among conspecific trees provides greater potential for growth in variable and inconstant environments (Keith et al. 2017; Carvalho & Ribeiro 2018), or even plant ontogeny, with plants of different ages growing in the edge, while long‐established adult plants dominate the forest interior (SP Ribeiro pers. obs.); and (2) lower abundance of the dominant specialist herbivorous can act as interaction hubs connecting all plants in the network (Tabeni & Ojeda 2003).

Despite the absence of individual trait measurements in the high‐impact edge, Carvalho and Ribeiro (2018) found morphological and allometric differences in M. fistulifera individuals of the interior forest and low‐impact edge. Population patches of M. fistulifera in different areas (e.g. natural and anthropogenic environments) have been studied for over 18 years in the PERD (Ribeiro et al., unpublished data). In general, it is expected that the greater the disturbance in the edge, the greater morphological heterogeneity (e.g. number of branches) within the population of M. fistulifera (Carvalho & Ribeiro 2018). For instance, the constant disturbance in edges creates gaps in the canopy, favouring the growth and emergence of new individuals (Ribeiro et al. 2008). This fact may have created specific interactions between certain herbivorous insect species and certain M. fistulifera individuals within developmental or size classes (Cornelissen et al. 2008).

In conclusion, our study provides evidence that forest fragmentation and edges affect the diversity of herbivorous insects, but preserve the way these insects interact with pioneer tree species in the Brazilian Atlantic forest. Our results for the ecological networks between M. fistulifera and its herbivorous insects showed that specialist herbivorous, which dominate the interactions within the population in preserved forest environments, had a lower frequency in forest edges, but the topology of these networks were maintained. Instead of a highly connected network where herbivorous can eat and control plant growth, forest edges hold highly specialised, poorly connected networks where populations of a few facultative herbivorous are limited to specific trees in a clumped distribution. The oversimplification of the network, through reduced diversity, can destabilise the interaction outcomes and enable pioneer species to prevail over new ones, slowing down natural succession in the edge and the forest traits restoration as a whole.
